content.problemStatement:
Nested loop best practices are essential to ensure code readability and efficiency. \
Let us look at the code used to generate the right angled triangle.
```cpp
#include 
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int n;
    cin >> n;

    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        for (int j = 1; j <= i; j++) {
            cout << "* ";
        }
        cout << "\n";
    }

    return 0;
}
```
Best practices
- Clear Indentation: Properly indent nested loops to improve code readability. \
Indent each inner loop one level from its outer loop.
- Use Descriptive Variable Names: Use meaningful variable names for loop control variables to enhance code understanding. 
- Limit Complexity: In this example, we are printing a simple pattern, so nested loops are appropriate.\
However, for more complex tasks, consider breaking down the problem into smaller functions or using alternative approaches.
- Avoid Unnecessary Nesting: Use nested loops only when needed!!! 
- Efficiency Considerations: For this simple pattern, efficiency is not a concern. \
However, if you're dealing with a large number of iterations, you might need to optimize the loops or consider alternative solutions.

